Of course. Here is a plan for the educational webpage, followed by the code to create it.

<Thinking>
### 1. Project Structure

I'll create a single-page Next.js application designed to teach a specific chemistry problem. The file structure will be modular to keep components lean and maintainable.

-   `app/layout.tsx`: Root layout, sets up fonts and basic page structure.
-   `app/page.tsx`: The main page component that assembles all the instructional sections.
-   `components/`: Directory for the various instructional sections.
    -   `IntroductionSection.tsx`: Sets the real-world context of aspirin synthesis.
    -   `ConceptualStepsSection.tsx`: Implements the Concrete-Representational-Abstract (CRA) model.
    -   `ProblemSolvingSection.tsx`: Guides students through the F.O.P.S. strategy for the main problem.
    -   `PracticeSection.tsx`: An interactive, client-side component for scaffolded practice.
    -   `TransferProblemsSection.tsx`: A client-side component containing the near and far transfer problems with answer checking.
    -   `MetacognitionSection.tsx`: Provides metacognitive prompts using an accordion.
-   `components/ui/`: Will house the shadcn/ui components (`Accordion`, `Button`, `Card`, `Input`, `Separator`).
-   `lib/utils.ts`: Standard utility file for `cn` from shadcn/ui.
-   `public/`: Will contain placeholder images for the lab setup and molecular models.
-   Standard Next.js config files: `tailwind.config.ts`, `next.config.mjs`, etc.

### 2. Styling

-   **Framework**: Tailwind CSS for utility-first styling.
-   **UI Library**: I will use shadcn/ui for its accessibility and modern design. Specifically, I'll need `Card` for content blocks, `Button` for interactions, `Input` for practice problems, `Accordion` for the metacognition section, and `Separator` for visual dividers.
-   **Color Palette**: A professional, educational theme with a neutral base (slate grays, white) and a primary accent color like teal or green for interactive elements and highlights. I will avoid blue and indigo.
-   **Responsiveness**: The design will be fully responsive, using flexbox and grid layouts to ensure it looks great on desktops, tablets, and mobile devices.

### 3. Images and Media

-   I'll use placeholder images to represent the visual elements required.
    -   `lab-setup.svg`: A simple diagram of a chemistry lab setup for the "Concrete" stage.
    -   `molecular-models.svg`: Illustrations of the molecules involved (salicylic acid, aspirin) for the "Representational" stage.
    -   `student-scientist.svg`: A friendly character illustration for the introduction to make the page more engaging.

### 4. The Chemistry Problem

-   **Core Problem**: A classic stoichiometry problem‚Äîcalculating the theoretical yield of aspirin from a known mass of a reactant (salicylic acid). This is a foundational concept in chemistry.
-   **Near-Transfer Problem**: A similar stoichiometry problem but in a different context (e.g., photosynthesis), requiring the same calculation steps (mass -> moles -> mole ratio -> mass).
-   **Far-Transfer Problem**: A problem that uses the same proportional reasoning but in a completely different chemistry domain, like gas laws (Boyle's Law: P‚ÇÅV‚ÇÅ = P‚ÇÇV‚ÇÇ). This tests the student's ability to abstract the underlying mathematical model.

### 5. Interactivity and State Management

-   The `PracticeSection` and `TransferProblemsSection` will require user input and state management. I will use React's `useState` hook for this.
-   These components will be designated as Client Components with the `"use client"` directive at the top of their respective files. The rest of the page will be rendered on the server.
-   Simple logic will be implemented to check the user's answers and provide immediate feedback (e.g., changing border colors to green for correct or red for incorrect).

### 6. Accessibility

-   I will use semantic HTML elements (`<main>`, `<section>`, `<h1>`, etc.).
-   All images will have descriptive `alt` text.
-   Interactive form elements (`<input>`, `<button>`) will have associated `<label>`s (sometimes using the `sr-only` class for accessibility).
-   The use of shadcn/ui components will ensure that accessibility best practices for ARIA roles and keyboard navigation are followed.
</Thinking>

### Step 1: Set up your Next.js project

First, create a new Next.js project with TypeScript and Tailwind CSS.

```bash
npx create-next-app@latest . --typescript --eslint --tailwind --app --turbopack --yes
```

### Step 2: Install shadcn/ui

Initialize shadcn/ui and add the components we'll need.

```bash
npx shadcn-ui@latest init
```

Choose `Default` for the base color, `Slate` for the CSS variables, and accept the other defaults. Then, add the following components:

```bash
npx shadcn-ui@latest add card button input accordion separator
```

### Step 3: Create Placeholder Images

Create a `public` folder in your project's root directory. Inside `public`, create the following SVG files. You can use any placeholder content.

**`public/student-scientist.svg`**
```xml
<svg width="100" height="100" viewBox="0 0 100 100" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
  <rect width="100" height="100" fill="#E2E8F0"/>
  <text x="50" y="55" font-family="Arial" font-size="12" text-anchor="middle" fill="#475569">Student</text>
</svg>
```

**`public/lab-setup.svg`**
```xml
<svg width="100" height="100" viewBox="0 0 100 100" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
  <rect width="100" height="100" fill="#E2E8F0"/>
  <text x="50" y="55" font-family="Arial" font-size="12" text-anchor="middle" fill="#475569">Lab Setup</text>
</svg>
```

**`public/molecular-models.svg`**
```xml
<svg width="100" height="100" viewBox="0 0 100 100" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
  <rect width="100" height="100" fill="#E2E8F0"/>
  <text x="50" y="55" font-family="Arial" font-size="12" text-anchor="middle" fill="#475569">Molecules</text>
</svg>
```

### Step 4: Create the Components

Now, create the component files inside the `components` directory.

